  "method": "We propose Conditional Subnetwork Activation (CSA), a single model trained to expose multiple, input-dependent compute paths at inference. Each backbone block contains two parallel branches: a light, local-processing path (e.g., gated MLP or depthwise-conv MLP) and a heavier, global-context path (e.g., attention). A tiny router (shared across tokens or operating on token groups) chooses which branch(es) to execute per block given a cheap summary of the current hidden state. During training, we apply stochastic branch dropout to force both branches to be individually competent and to encourage graceful degradation when only one is active. We add a soft FLOPs budget regularizer on the router’s expected choices so the model learns to allocate compute where it pays off most.\n\nTo avoid running unnecessary depth, we attach auxiliary prediction heads at several layers and adopt a dynamic early-exit rule driven by layer-wise saturation: compute the cosine similarity between consecutive hidden states; when similarity exceeds a calibrated threshold and the corresponding head’s confidence is sufficient, we stop and emit the output. For autoregressive generation, we decay the threshold across decoding steps and cap minimum layers to avoid premature exits on early tokens. This turns depth into an on-demand resource, activating more layers only for difficult inputs or steps.\n\nWithin each block, we further make width conditional by nesting smaller channel slices inside larger ones. Linear and attention projections are parameterized in a Matryoshka style so the first w% of channels approximate a competent subnetwork and larger widths strictly extend it. We implement this as masked matrix multiplications/grouped projections that compute only the selected slice, avoiding kernel recompilations. Training samples widths per batch (e.g., 25/50/100%), distills from the full-width path to narrower slices, and jointly optimizes the task loss so all widths remain aligned.\n\nAt inference, CSA follows a progressive schedule that minimizes overhead: start with a narrow width and only the light branch for a small number of layers; if the saturation metric indicates underfit or the head is uncertain, escalate compute by enabling the heavy branch and/or increasing width for subsequent layers; otherwise, early-exit. Routers operate with hysteresis and a global budget controller to stabilize decisions and respect latency targets. Optionally, a lightweight token scorer can route only the top-p tokens through the heavy branch while the remainder stay on the light path, providing additional sparsity without architectural changes.",
  "rationale": "Dense models waste compute by executing the full depth, width, and global-context machinery on every input. CSA reduces all three dimensions adaptively: branch routing decides whether to pay for global context per block; early exiting truncates depth once representations saturate; and Matryoshka-style slicing executes only the necessary width. Because branches are trained with dropout and slices are co-trained with distillation, any activated subnetwork remains well-formed, limiting accuracy loss under reduced compute.\n\nThe key is to couple low-cost, reliable signals to gating. Layer-wise cosine similarity provides a model-internal saturation proxy that generalizes across tasks and supports safe early exit. Branch dropout makes per-branch activation robust, enabling per-input routing without retraining. Nested weight slicing turns width into a knob the router can adjust on-the-fly using the same backbone, avoiding multiple models. Together, these mechanisms conditionally activate only the relevant subnetwork for each input and deliver substantial inference savings with bounded quality impact.",
