  "method": "We propose Context-Conditioned ProtoGated Subnetworks (C2PS): replace each dense block with a thin, always-on shared trunk in parallel with a pool of E residual experts. A lightweight router activates only the top-k experts per input (or per token for sequence models), so most parameters remain idle for any given example. The trunk preserves a stable, general pathway; the experts provide capacity that is selectively engaged.\n\nRouting is fast and data-aware. Compute a global context embedding once per input (e.g., CLS/mean-pooled features) and feed it to all routers. At each block, the router forms a compact local summary of the incoming features (e.g., per-token or spatially pooled) and scores it against a bank of learned prototypes using cosine similarity with a sharpening nonlinearity. The router fuses local scores with a FiLM-style modulation from the global context to make context-aware, top-k selections. To keep routing overhead low even with larger E, we maintain a streaming top-k via limited-scope competition: only adjacent near-top candidates are compared and swapped until convergence to the k winners, avoiding full O(E^2) pairwise ranking.\n\nTraining is end-to-end with standard task loss plus: (1) a load-balancing regularizer to prevent expert collapse; (2) structured group sparsity on expert parameters that encourages specialization and prunes unused paths into clean subnetworks; and (3) a gradual sparsity curriculum that anneals k from dense toward the target budget, stabilizing early learning. We use straight-through or Gumbel-TopK estimators for discrete routing, and distill from a dense teacher (or a late-training snapshot) to mitigate routing noise while experts specialize.\n\nInference is strictly conditional: for each layer, compute the router, dispatch activations only to the selected experts, and aggregate their outputs (e.g., sum or weighted sum) with the trunk via residual addition. Budgets are adjustable at runtime by tuning k or the routing temperature. For transformers, apply C2PS to MLPs (per-token routing) and optionally to attention heads (per-head routing); for CNNs, gate residual bottlenecks or channel groups. When routing uncertainty is high (e.g., low prototype margin), fall back to a larger k or the trunk-only path, preserving accuracy under tight budgets.",
  "rationale": "C2PS achieves conditional compute by learning which subnetwork is relevant for each input and only activating that subset. Prototype-based scoring yields sharp, discriminative routing while remaining inexpensive, and the global-context modulation aligns per-token/per-block choices with the sequence- or image-level intent. Group sparsity and a sparsity curriculum shape experts into truly distinct competencies so that activating only a few preserves accuracy. Load balancing avoids overused experts and keeps throughput stable.\n\nCompared to static pruning, C2PS adapts per input and per location (token/region), capturing input heterogeneity without incurring dense FLOPs. Compared to naive MoE, the prototype router is lighter, better regularized, and stabilized by a shared trunk and knowledge distillation, delivering strong accuracy–efficiency trade-offs and controllable latency.",
